By Jeff Evans

   
   
   
   
   We've tried, we really have tried, to be reasonable, sensitive,
   modest...downright Canadian in our attempts to curb the techno-lust
   that lurks withinmany PC users, and within virtually every computer
   journalist.
   
   We've all read the ads in the computer magazines, and secretly longed
   to ownthe niftiest sounding Power User's systems on the market. When
   it comes towanting more computing power than any sane person really
   needs, many of us areguilty of committing several of the Seven Deadly
   Sins (Lust? Gluttony? Greed?Envy?).
   
   Although we've tried to encourage you, our readers, to ignore the hype
   aboutthe latest and greatest (and most expensive) technology, in favor
   of"appropriate technology"-- affordable, modestly performing products
   that meetcurrent needs adequately -- we suspect that, deep down, you'd
   at least like tokick the tires on the hottest PCs on the lot. So, this
   month, let's just try toimagine what we might buy if we had an
   unlimited PC toy budget.
   
   To make the process more respectable, we'll even describe the real
   world,actual business applications that these leading edge systems
   might excel at(when we aren't using them to play Doom, that is). If we
   want to persuade anunwary boss (or spouse) that we actually need to
   buy one of these Maseratis ofthe computing world, it helps to be able
   to put forward a business case forbuying a high-end PC, as a kind of
   fig leaf to cover our naked technomania.
   
   We want our dream machines, we want them now, and we want them bad.
   
GreatExpectations

   In 1993, when the BAPCo consortium established a benchmark value of
   100 for itsSYSMARK 93 benchmark suite, the computer they used to set
   the performancestandard was a then-state-of-the-art Intel DX2/33 MHz
   based system with a fastgraphics card and an unusually generous 8 MB
   of RAM. As we'll see in thissurvey, a similarly leading edge Intel
   Pentium-based system of today routinelycranks out a SYSMARK benchmark
   score of about 300. There's been an effectivetripling of overall
   computer power in the last two years or so.
   
   Whether we "need" all this power to write a letter is a moot point.
   For seriousbusiness applications like CAD, multimedia, digital video,
   voice recognition,digital audio, digital photography, simulation and
   VR, desktop publishing, andnetwork server provision, the increase in
   PC performance and reliability isreshaping the way much of our work,
   play and education is conducted. Thisrecent 300 percent increase in
   performance is not a solution, exactly, thoughit makes many new things
   possible. Rather it is a step on a path of computerevolution, whose
   possible consequences we barely understand.
   
BeyondIntel and Win3.1

   In 1995, for the first time, there are a variety of real alternatives
   to Intelfor high end PC users. Silicon Graphics' workstations (which
   include thecomputers used to create the effects in Jurassic Park and
   Terminator2) are the professional's choice for 3D graphics and
   animation, VirtualReality, and Computer Aided Design.
   
   NEC Technologies has adopted the MIPS RISC processor as the basis for
   a line ofhigh-powered PCs that are used by Microsoft for developing
   Windows NT. DigitalEquipment Corp., after spending over a billion
   dollars developing its Alphachip, is finally seeing that effort pay
   off in powerful PCs, servers andworkstations.
   
   The other major partners in the PowerPC consortium, IBM and Motorola,
   are bothbringing high-end PowerPC-based personal computers to market.
   One thing to noteis that, although all of these platforms based on
   exotic processors can runregular Windows software in a kind of
   emulation mode, they are designed to runthe Windows NT operating
   system (with the exception of Silicon Graphics, whichruns a version of
   UNIX). Windows NT is the core of the business case for thenew RISC
   PCs.
   
   Because of this multiplicity of choices for would-be Power Users, this
   surveyis composed of two sections: the first is a benchmark comparison
   of high-end,Intel-based Windows PCs from major Canadian suppliers,
   with the usual tables ofconfigurations and performance, created with
   the aid of the BAPCo SYSMARK 95benchmark suite.
   
   
   
