   price/performance standard that the other PC makers willhave to strain
   to catch up to.
   
   The other winner is the Comtex Mach 5 P55CMS, based on a 133
   MHzprocessor. It has a very large 1.6 GB hard drive, and offers the
   best speedwe've yet encountered in TCP Test Labs surveys. The overall
   Windowsperformance was about 14 percent better than the Dell, and the
   price was about20 percent higher. These units represent the peak of
   price performance for theindividual PC user in Canada in the summer of
   1995.
   
   
   
   Power Systems Part 2
   
   Pentium? Whuzzat?
   
   
   
   In addition to the mainstream Intel PCs, a new generation of RISC
   basedplatforms are offering extraordinary performance for the power
   user. Most ofthem run Windows NT, Microsoft's still-poorly understood
   high-end operatingsystem. NT is often chosen as the O/S for network
   servers, where itscrash-resistance, hardware-independence, and
   multitasking ability lend it to"mission critical" applications. NT is
   also coming into wider use as theoperating system for high end
   personal workstations. Typical applications areCAD, Animation, 3D
   design and rendering. Several vendors have recently come tomarket with
   personal systems based on one or another of the common RISCprocessors,
   and running NT.
   
   
   
   Amiware Post Station: This is one of the most unusual computer
   systemswe've seen. Based on the DEC 21164 Alpha processor running at
   266 MHz, this isa 3D rendering, animation and digital video editing
   and effects system.Processing is done at a speed of 470 floating point
   SPEC. The system runsWindows NT and, in addition to the Alpha chip, it
   can alternatively accommodateMIPS or Intel processors in lieu of
   Alpha. The motherboard has two SCSI IIcontrollers, allowing the high
   speed transfer of massive amounts of data thatanimation and video
   processing requires. The O/S supports RAID 1 hard drivearrays.
   
   The basic Post Station comes with 2 MB of 12 Ns cache RAM, a 17-inch
   Viewsonicmonitor, 64 MB of 70 ns parity RAM (expandable to 512 MB of
   RAM), a 2 GBQuantum Atlas SCSI hard drive, a Sony CD-ROM drive,
   Ethernet card, DiamondStealth 64 with 4 MB VRAM, MS keyboard and
   mouse, and MS Windows NT 3.5, for$22,000. The main virtue of this
   system is sheer speed for specialized graphicsand video tasks. Long
   time computer animation buffs may remember the famousVideo Toaster on
   the Amiga, used for creating the effects on Babylon Five andSeaquest
   DSV.
   
   The Lightwave 3D animation software originally developed for the Video
   Toasterruns over 50 times faster on the Post Station than on an
   original Amiga4000/040 with a Video Toaster installed. Amblin Imaging
   (a Spielberg companywhich does some of the effects for Star Trek) is
   among the professional usersof this system. The Post Station is
   considered to be 4 times faster than aSilicon Graphics Indy, and 2
   times faster than an Indigo2. For the power userwho wants a desktop
   system to help create the next Jurassic Park, this is agood choice.
   
   
   
   IBM Personal Computer Power Series: After developing terrific
   RISCprocessor technology, IBM then failed to market it effectively for
   nearly adecade. As a result of its collaboration with Apple and
   Motorola in thedevelopment of the PowerPC processor family, however,
   IBM has finally beenmoved to bring affordable RISC technology to its
   high end PC line. The 830 and850 models are built around PowerPC 604
   chips running at 100 MHz (the 850 canalso be fitted with 120 MHz or
   133 MHz models). These systems can run OS/2Warp, Windows NT, AIX v.4
   for clients, and Solaris (PowerPC edition, whenavailable).
   
   
   
   Motorola PowerStac RISC PC DT604-100 and MT604-100: As one of
   theoriginal partners in the PowerPC consortium, it was perhaps to be
   expected thatMotorola would be interested in doing more than just
   manufacturing the chips.Somewhat analogous to the IBM Power Series,
   the Power Stac PCs are PowerPCbased personal systems designed to offer
   RISC performance and NT reliability toindividual users. In their
   initial incarnation, these PCs run UNIX (AIX) andare "Windows NT
   Ready," but are intended to be compatible with "other
   operatingsystems" (such as OS/2?) as those are ported over.
   
   As part of an overall solution that includes the larger PowerStac
   servers,these PCs make sense. However, it would seem that Motorola may
   need to get moreexperience in the PC market, and offer more
   compatibility, lower price andbetter performance, if this is to be
   more than a niche product.
   
   
   
   NEC RISCstation 2200: Of all the new high end PCs running the
   NToperating system, NEC's offerings are probably the most credible as
   an optionfor a serious business computing solution. NEC pioneered the
   high performance,RISC NT market when it made an early decision to
   adopt the MIPS processor asthe basis for the first NT workstations.
   Microsoft standardized on the earlyNEC models as the original platform
   for Windows NT. As Windows NT has grown,NEC's expertise in RISC
   technology has also increased. The model 2200 is thelatest NEC NT PC,
   and it offers high performance, multimedia flexibility, andhigh
   reliability at a reasonable cost. The RISCstation 2200 is based on a
   200MHz NEC VR4400MC processor. This is an NEC version of the R4400
   chip created bya subsidiary of Silicon Graphics, MIPS, Ltd.
   
   To encourage the spread and adoption of SGI technology, SGI has made
   itpossible for any manufacturer who agrees to maintain compatibility
   with theMIPS processor standard to manufacture their own versions of
   the processor. TheNEC RISCstation has some familiar PC features - PCI
   bus, PC style audio andgraphics - but it also has unique features,
   such as a special 3D animationprocessor to give extremely high
   rendering performance.
   
   
   
   Apple PowerMac 8100/110: When we started this survey, the fastest
   Macfrom Apple was the 8100/110. When the review unit arrived at our
   offices, wechased away the regular crowd of Mac enthusiasts and set it
   up. When weconnected it to its AV-style monitor (which either takes a
   regular video cablefeed, or a combined video/audio output from the
   8100), and powered it up, wewere initially shocked by its apparently
   sluggish performance. Quickly, wedetermined that a previous reviewer
   had polluted the PowerMac nativeenvironment by turning on some
   utilities based on old style Motorola 68x code.The PowerMac is
   perfectly happy running most old Mac software, but itsperformance
   really drags unless it is running "native" PowerMac programs.
   
   After turning off the offending old software, the system speeded up
   incredibly.In particular, software that makes good use of the
   PowerMac's strongfloating-point calculating ability (such as 3D
   software, and Adobe Photoshop)is faster than any Pentium.
   
   We were very impressed by the 8100 until a few days before this
   article was togo to press, when Apple announced the new PowerMac 9500,
   which is claimed to betwice as fast as the 8100. Our opinion of the
   8100 went from profound respectand desire-to-own, to irritation at
   being in the same room with a computerwhose time had passed,
   seemingly, almost before it had arrived.
   
   For all the progress that Windows has made, the Mac -- any Mac -- is
   easier andmore pleasant to use, especially for creative applications.
   The PowerMacs haveenough muscle to outproduce a Pentium based system
   in most graphics andcommunications applications, though at a higher
   initial cost. Apple claims thatthe money you spend upfront on their
   hardware is more than repaid by the lowersystem lifetime costs for
   training, service, and increased productivity.
   
   
   
   Silicon Graphics Indy: This entry level "personal workstation" from
   theSilicon Graphics line of computers is perhaps the ultimate power
   users' PC. Forone thing, its operating system is a flavor of UNIX,
   which is both mysteriousand powerful, like the hardware. Everything
   about the Indy is a little exoticto the ordinary PC user. It comes
   with a tiny digital video camera (the betterto do teleconferencing
   with). It doesn't necessarily come with anexternally-accessible drive
   that you can insert some kind of disk, cartridge ortape into (the
   assumption is that the Indy is on a network, where not everybodyneeds
   a floppy drive). How do you attach a modem to it? (Usually you don't
   --you're supposed to be on a network, remember?).
   
   However, once you start to figure it out, the Indy turns into a thing
   ofbeauty. Its graphical user interface is very elegant, and is tied in
   with theunderlying UNIX command line interface in such a way that you
   can do everythingby point and click, or by command line, or any
   mixture of the two. It's aperfectly multitasking system, in a way that
   Mac and Windows users can onlydream of. And it's fast. Based on the
   MIPS R4400 processor, it's at least asfast as any of the current
   PowerMacs. And, for greater speed, the Indy isdesigned to seamlessly
   connect to larger SGI computers, where it can shareprocessing tasks
   with its bigger siblings.
   
   The main uses of the Indy are for 3D animation, high level desktop
   publishing,digital photography, video and CAD. There is excellent
   native software in allof these areas, though compared to much PC
   software it is quite expensive. Oncewe figured out how to attach
   external drives to our demo unit (quite easy, viaa well implemented
   SCSI interface) we loaded and tested Alias Animator 6.0,Adobe
   Photoshop and Illustrator on the system, and found that, in spite of
   analmost old-fashioned, clunky user interface, it is incredibly
   powerful, fastand flexible as a media creation tool. The Indy we
   tested was configured as aWebforce Internet system, and unlike the
   often crude World Wide Web authoringsolutions we've seen on other
   platforms, this is a professional onlinepublishing system. SGI claims
   to be making rapid strides in the Web publishingboom.
   
AndThe Winners Are: 
ToBe Determined

    The models we looked at were pretty diverse: UNIX, PowerMac,
   MIPS/NT,Alpha/NT, Dual Pentium/NT. It isn't possible to compare these
   products directlywith each other, though a few comments may be in
   order. First, although the newPowerPC based desktop PCs from IBM and
   Motorola look promising for high endsolutions, they have a long way to
   go in terms of building a user base and somecompelling software
   applications. They are also expensive.
   
   The latest PowerMacs (especially the 9500) offer superior graphics
   andanimation power, and a part of a well-established computing
   platform and usercommunity. If Apple follows its usual procedure, we
   can expect to see the priceof the 8100/110 decline quickly due to the
   advent of the 9500.
   
   The big surprises were the NEC RISC Station and the Silicon Graphics
   Indy. TheNEC product is a surprisingly mature, complete system,
   reflecting NEC's earlycommitment to RISC and NT technologies, and it
   is a very viable, usable optionfor the serious power user. The SGI
   Indy is the affordable entry-level model ina range of computers that
   is almost infinitely scaleable and compatible, up tothe highest range
   of supercomputing capability. It has some terrific 3D andInternet
   publishing solutions available, and is highly recommendable in
   theseniche markets.
   
   The DEC Alpha-based Post Station is a sort of technological mutation:
   adedicated video/animation system that is incredibly powerful,
   thoughspecialized in its possible application. With the exception of
   the PowerMacline, which has passed its millionth unit sold, it remains
   to be seen which ofthese other systems will find a significant number
   of users from within theranks of the PC community.
   
